16. Pass by Value vs Pass by Reference

JavaScript is always pass-by-value.

For primitives, the value itself is copied.
For objects, the reference value (memory address) is copied, so two variables point to the same object.

Example

let a=10;

let b=a;

b=20;
a=10

b=20

Objects

let obj1={name:"Lucky"};

let obj2=obj1;

Both point to the same object.

