20. Lexical Scoping

A function can access variables from its parent scope.

Example

let name="Lucky";

function show(){

    console.log(name);

}

show();

Output

Lucky

JavaScript decides scope based on where the function is written, not where it is called.

21. Explain This Code (Closure)
var scope = "global";

function check(){

    var scope = "local";

    function f(){

        return scope;

    }

    return f;

}

Suppose

let result = check();

console.log(result());

Output

local
Why?

Because f() remembers the variables from the scope where it was created, not where it is called.

This is called a Closure.

